        <item>
            <title>Don&#39;t install too many Joomla extensions</title>
            <pubDate>Tue, 29 Mar 2016 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
            <link>https://www.joomlatools.com/blog/2016/03/dont-install-too-many-joomla-extensions/</link>
            <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.joomlatools.com/blog/2016/03/dont-install-too-many-joomla-extensions/</guid>
            <description>
                <![CDATA[
                
                    <img width="800" src="https://www.joomlatools.com/images/blog/2016/extensions-manager.jpg" alt="" />
                
                <p>Thanks to the huge collection of Joomla extensions almost any functionality you can think of is available in a few clicks. Trying new extensions is fun, but don’t add one extension after another just because you can.</p>

<!--more-->

<h2 id="how-many-extensions-can-i-install">How many extensions can I install?</h2>

<p>Joomla has no limit in the amount of extensions (plugins, components, modules and templates) you can install.</p>

<p>Your website will work fine as long as all the extensions are compatible with Joomla, each other and the server environment. However, never install unfamiliar extensions in live websites.</p>

<h2 id="try-in-a-separate-installation">Try in a separate installation</h2>

<p>The best way to discover if an extension really fits your needs is by trying it yourself. It’s good to start exploring an extension in a separate Joomla installation. Or, even better, in a local copy of your live website.</p>

<p>Using our <a href="https://www.joomlatools.com/developer/tools/vagrant/">Vagrant box</a> you can install new Joomla sites locally in seconds.</p>

<h2 id="uninstall-what-you-dont-need">Uninstall what you don’t need</h2>

<p>Make sure to check all installed extensions before moving the site into production. Maybe the requirements of the client changed and you had to use another extension but forgot to uninstall the previous one.</p>

<p>Do a full backup before doing anything so you can always restore any error. Oh, and don’t forget to backup, the backup!</p>

<h2 id="dedicated-support">Dedicated support</h2>

<p>Even the best Joomla extension can break and often in the worst possible moment. Make sure every installed extension is actively supported. So you won’t be on your own when you encounter a problem.</p>

<p>Need help? We offer dedicated <a href="https://support.joomlatools.com">support</a> for our <a href="https://www.joomlatools.com/extensions/">extensions</a> and also <a href="https://www.joomlatools.com/enterprise/">enterprise consulting services</a>.</p>

                ]]>
            </description>
        </item>
        
        <item>
            <title>Say hi to FILEman 3.0 beta</title>
            <pubDate>Thu, 24 Mar 2016 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
            <link>https://www.joomlatools.com/blog/2016/03/say-hi-to-fileman-30-beta/</link>
            <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.joomlatools.com/blog/2016/03/say-hi-to-fileman-30-beta/</guid>
            <description>
                <![CDATA[
                
                    <img width="800" src="https://www.joomlatools.com/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_beta.png" alt="" />
                
                <p>We are happy to announce the <strong>beta release of FILEman 3.0</strong>. This new major version brings a load of new features to make file management on your Joomla sites <strong>better and easier</strong>.</p>

<!--more-->

<p>New features:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="#attachments">Attachments</a>, attach documents and images to Joomla articles</li>
  <li><a href="#modules">Two new modules</a>, Files &amp; Folders module</li>
  <li><a href="#frontend-management">Frontend management</a>, manage files without administrator access</li>
  <li><a href="#new-uploader">New uploader</a>, compact and easier to use</li>
  <li><a href="#configuration">Configuration</a>, independent configuration settings</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="attachments">Attachments</h2>

<p>FILEman 3.0 comes with <strong>built-in attachments support</strong>. Just create or edit an article and click on the new attachments editor button to bring up the attachments window for adding and removing attachments from the article.</p>

<figure>
    <picture>
        
        <source media="(min-width: 400px)" srcset="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_managment.png?w=590&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_managment.png?w=885&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 1.5x,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_managment.png?w=1180&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 2x" />
        
        <source media="(min-width: 0px)" srcset="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_managment.png?w=400&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_managment.png?w=600&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 1.5x,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_managment.png?w=800&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 2x" />
        <img class="image-blog-styled" src="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_managment.png?w=590&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90" alt="Screenshot of FILEman attachment management UI" />
    </picture>
    
    <figcaption><p>Screenshot of FILEman attachment management UI</p>
</figcaption>
    
</figure>

<p>Atachments are displayed below the articles content. Each attachment is displayed with its download link and thumbnails are available for images. A click over an image thumbnail will bring a <strong>full sized preview</strong> of the image file.</p>

<figure>
    <picture>
        
        <source media="(min-width: 400px)" srcset="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_frontend.png?w=590&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_frontend.png?w=885&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 1.5x,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_frontend.png?w=1180&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 2x" />
        
        <source media="(min-width: 0px)" srcset="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_frontend.png?w=400&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_frontend.png?w=600&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 1.5x,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_frontend.png?w=800&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 2x" />
        <img class="image-blog-styled" src="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_attachments_frontend.png?w=590&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90" alt="Screenshot of FILEman attachments in article content" />
    </picture>
    
    <figcaption><p>Screenshot of FILEman attachments in article content</p>
</figcaption>
    
</figure>

<p>Do you need to customize the look and feel of attachments in your articles? … fear not. You can completely modify the way attachments are displayed by simply using <strong>template overrides</strong>.</p>

<p>Any resource that exposes a text editor may support attachments through FILEman. This beta release includes support for attaching files to Joomla articles. We are planning on <strong>supporting other components</strong> in future releases.</p>

<h2 id="modules">Modules</h2>

<p>Two new modules make their entrance in this version:</p>

<h3 id="fileman---files">FILEman - Files</h3>

<p>This module displays a list of files in any module position. Files that are listed can come from one or multiple folders and be filtered using a variety of filters.</p>

<h3 id="fileman---folders">FILEman - Folders</h3>

<p>This module provides a list of folders that gets displayed in a module position. Folders can be based on a specific root folder and the module offers support to show the whole folder hierarchy.</p>

<figure>
    <picture>
        
        <source media="(min-width: 400px)" srcset="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_modules.png?w=590&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_modules.png?w=885&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 1.5x,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_modules.png?w=1180&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 2x" />
        
        <source media="(min-width: 0px)" srcset="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_modules.png?w=400&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_modules.png?w=600&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 1.5x,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_modules.png?w=800&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 2x" />
        <img class="image-blog-styled" src="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_modules.png?w=590&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90" alt="Screenshot of FILEman Files and Folders modules" />
    </picture>
    
    <figcaption><p>Screenshot of FILEman Files and Folders modules</p>
</figcaption>
    
</figure>

<p>Both modules are <strong>highly customizable</strong> and can be configured to accommodate different case scenarios.</p>

<h2 id="frontend-management">Frontend management</h2>

<p>We have further improved frontend management features to make it possible to manage your file listings without needing administrator access.</p>

<p>The beta release allows users with delete permissions to <strong>delete files</strong> through the frontend user interface.</p>

<figure>
    <picture>
        
        <source media="(min-width: 400px)" srcset="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_frontend_delete.png?w=590&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_frontend_delete.png?w=885&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 1.5x,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_frontend_delete.png?w=1180&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 2x" />
        
        <source media="(min-width: 0px)" srcset="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_frontend_delete.png?w=400&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_frontend_delete.png?w=600&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 1.5x,
                https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_frontend_delete.png?w=800&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90 2x" />
        <img class="image-blog-styled" src="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_frontend_delete.png?w=590&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90" alt="Screenshot of frontend delete interface" />
    </picture>
    
    <figcaption><p>Screenshot of frontend delete interface</p>
</figcaption>
    
</figure>

<p>This is the first step of many towards frontend management with FILEman. We are currently working on providing full frontend file management capabilities including the ability of <strong>adding folders from site</strong>. We aim to have these new features ready for the stable release.</p>

<h2 id="new-uploader">New Uploader</h2>

<p>We have rebuilt our file uploader to make it both more <strong>compact and easier to use</strong>.</p>

<figure>
    <picture>
        
        <source media="(min-width: 400px)" srcset="https://joomlatools.imgix.net/images/blog/2016/fileman_30_uploader.png?w=590&amp;auto=format&amp;q=90,
